				<listPerson>
					<person xml:id="ehri_et_morgensternova_ruth">
						<persName>Morgensternová, Ruth</persName>
					</person>
					<person xml:id="ehri_et_schickova_helena">
						<persName>Schicková, Helena</persName>
						<note><p>1909–1992</p><p>She lived in Prague and worked as a clerk. In 1943 she was deported to the Theresienstadt (Terezín)
								ghetto, where she has survived until the liberation. After the war she was involved in the Documentation campaign
								(Dokumentační akce). In 1949, Schicková emigrated to Israel.</p></note>
					</person>
					<person xml:id="ehri_et_gerzonova_berta">
						<persName>Gerzonová, Berta</persName>
						<note><p>1914–?</p><p>Born in Mukachevo, from 1939 she lived in Prague. Gerzonová was deported to the Theresienstadt (Terezín)
								ghetto in 1942, from which she was transported in autumn 1944 to Auschwitz-Birkenau. After the war she was one of the
								co-workers of the Documentation campaign (Dokumentační akce). She got married and moved with her husband to
								Slovakia.</p></note>
					</person>
					<person xml:id="ehri_et_shek_zeev">
						<persName>Shek, Zeev</persName>
						<note><p>1920–1978</p><p>Born in Olomouc. Active in the Zionist movement, member of Maccabi Hatzair. In 1943 he was deported
								to the Theresienstadt (Terezín) ghetto, where he became one of the Hechalutz leaders. In autumn 1944 he was
								transported to Auschwitz-Birkenau. After the war he became one of the main initiator of the Documentation campaign
								(Dokumentační akce). In 1946 he emigrated to Palestine, where he worked for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and in the
								diplomatic services. In 1967 Sheck was appointed as the Israeli Ambassador in Vienna. In 1977 he was sent to serve as
								the Israeli Ambassador in Rome, where he has died one year later.</p></note>
					</person>
